A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Possible
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, our operators offering practically the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classical operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't miss it for a long time.
We have repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
ČTU (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, has confirmed it.
Thus, as a result of the European Commission's last steps in regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Czech Telecommunications Agency Council (ČTÚ), said on several occasions that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, has been chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network is apparently not much more likely (at present, he would find only difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a significant price reduction, to which the traditional operators had to react as well.
However, even before the introduction of such disturbances as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual Mobilking operator.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the country's fifth operator.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:phone in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network, which are relatively high.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer calls and good SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as illustrated by the example of Mobilking in Poland, merkering on an unusual target group can also constitute a good deal of publicity.
In fact, this operator is specifically aimed at men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept could also be found in us.
Miroslav Čepíký, Vodafone spokesperson: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
As far as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the success of this project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not very provocative.
Mobilking's launch will take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not been hiding its intention of launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time.
"We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services but also mobile.
And the sooner it'll be the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility several times with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations," said the spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So the future may be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At this point, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific ones.
For the time being, no subject provided with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with the O2: "We have not recorded for the moment a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate within such a limited timeframe, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Instead Vodafone directs his attention to the fulfilment of requests for his own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepýký said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think means most of our customers' inputs.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator meant an increase in competition, would have led to a lower price and thus to a lower profit.
So what good is it to make it easier for such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know what they mean in the fair. The joke accompanying the creation of the U:phone also bears witness to it.
The biggest apparent pressure on the ČTU, during the creation of the U:phone, was the one exercised by the T-Mobile company.
They testify to the information available to the public from the ČTU website.
Today, the U:phone is ready to serve as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "Competitive competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player will be subject, and especially its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems to be disconcerting.
However, this is not only the attitude of the ČTU, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in the economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in view of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator on the mobile market would be possible as a result of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the time being, because the offer of potential stakeholders has not given sufficient priority to classical operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of ÚOHS in response to our question.
A statement thus made would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of his position on the market, such a statement is more than overwhelming.
As Kristian Chalupa adds: "In addition, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in mobile phone service prices."
However, pressure in the sense of an honest functioning of the market and a price reduction is apparently not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is truly shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, resulting from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, is of course raised.
Similarly, a price of strictly identical fuel to all service stations is probably due to the accident and the hard fight against competition.
"The Office has not shown any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none of them have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator," Chalopa stated in her statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTU, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts suggest another vision of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on his network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying about the ÚOHS that three mobile operators occur in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many stakeholders (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Reconstituting responsibility for ČTU is a fairly common turn in communications, whereby ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to bring about the renewal of the Telecommunications Act, which has recently been adopted, to extend the ČTU's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
This is something that the representatives of the ÚOHS need to know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
That said, the operation of some kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own mobile phone prices list, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a matter of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms are generally available only to the electors.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company before the operator is a classic business client, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special offers of prices (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a return.
"If what you are saying happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and that could lead to a halt to the collaboration with the society in question," Martina Kemrová replied to our question regarding this problem.
However, it is unlikely that an echo of such an activity will not be achieved to those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
No operator shall, however, object to such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these firms bring them lasting benefits, and, at the same time, by opposition to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
Moreover, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it in the way of ordinary mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTU.
In addition, another question was raised at the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has relatively large powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea what would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When We Will Not Be the Most Precious Country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, classical operators were increasingly, less or less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that in the developed countries, regulatory bodies, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their clients, were involved.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are dealing with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is being discarded by passing it on to a close target.
As a result of the experience we have, we cannot escape the impression that the confusion in their skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw the stain after the cognac.
If the information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS can hardly remain unbearable in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymne has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national hymen.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech National Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new records of the national hymne Kde homev mój (Where is my country?).
The Hymne was re-registered by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with a heart and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžinková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremáš and Jaroslav Krkek are the authors of the hymne arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhalas (Czech public radio), he chose to interpret solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers, as well as the choir, had a good word, so that we could understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national hymen celebrates next year its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde namv můj held for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the theatre of the states) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), the original Czech piece of Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroop.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national hymen.
It will remain one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
