The repeaters of alcohol at the wheel will need to install the 'alcohol' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for alcoholism to install in his vehicle a system that prevents him from starting the vehicle in a state of gravity, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative has already been announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last for a year.
Its aim is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road re-education courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety but also the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Institute of Technology for Road Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to the statistics, between 30% and 75% of the motorists arrested for driving more than once in hibernation, the car resumes.
Alcohol would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the dress and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver’s alcohol rate is higher than the permitted one.
Its cost is over EUR 1,000 and is at the driver's charge.
In this respect, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced to 65% of the offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 people every year.
This measure only applies to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by regular means, but reform by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have an experimental one.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the Spanish socialist party that proposes to install this system in school buses as it was done in France.
