Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday's 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the world's most secure and effective blood suppliers.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously shaken by the blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the greed of the public, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer happen.
While Judge Krever was delaying his report, some provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said proudly that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Québec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, a new version of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease was seen in Europe when many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, the new version of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, were seen, which has been holding the strong since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports that when we do not know it and that a serious disease can result from it, in the event of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of those who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980 was refused.
But a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the principle of caution applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: nuclear acid tests (TAN) that directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the donor blood and not of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have been able to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This significantly reduced the risk of certain donors being infected without knowledge and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, this will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the head of Hema-Quebec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It must be constantly monitored," Dr. Décary went on to point out that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"The needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need recharge in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which averages only 3 per cent of the Québecs eligible for blood donation."
However, any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled in a country where malaria is used, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poor people are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and are no longer able to give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so tense, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving his blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone graffons, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec which also manages the only public blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was considered to be a biomedical waste consists of a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the establishment of our thousandth blood sample of cordon and is planned to take more than a thousand per year.
We should start by offering them for graffiti at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this program of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because Hema-Québec has no means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
