Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to halt the financial crisis that has been depleting Wall Street for months must still be maintained by both Houses of Congress.
It provides, inter alia, for better control by the electors of its implementation, for new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money committed, for new arrangements to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, as well as for a right to look at the salaries paid to the directors of the rescued companies.
US Secretary of Treasury, Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon.
