Hepatitis: When do we need to consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred miles of hepatitis virus sufferers in Hungary, but only seven miles of treatment follow. This is because patients often do not know they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g., food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, salt).
For travellers, it is recommended in any way to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a general malaise, weakness, stomach disease and nausea.
Then, on the skin and on the white of the eye, a visible jaundice develops, the salts become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only one patient in ten receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to a cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average of a population of three groups: people who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million people are infected with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advised to consult your doctor who is treating symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be healed if it is detected on time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On September 30, it is the world day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing the four world-wide diseases.
Its aim is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver caused by the virus, to the causes of its development and to the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
