The smart car imitates the boordon flights
What method would be best to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an existing barrier detector in nature?
For example, that one of the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, the Burdon bees gave the strategic idea of starting off at Nissan to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacles detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired auto-robotized control system, of type BR23C, which equipped bee quality, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, in oval form, which, in fact, looks much like our safe protective helmet - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and the brand's technological public relations.
The eye to the face of the bee plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the facet eye, engineers have addressed the idea of the laser telemeter.
He identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres before the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the ship's microprocessor, which turns it into a control immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a second fraction. Then the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently existing, this avoidr is entirely instinctive.
"If not, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and most internal layer of the protection envelope, a layer where collision is considered inevitable for the moment.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in an eyelid.
In contrast to the bees, the difference cannot go upward, downward or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the endless combinations that have the bees to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotating movement, acceleration and slowdown as drivers at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and with a higher energy concentration, making them longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less storage capacity.
This mechanism should only deal with a few signals coming in a second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers. Thus, it only uses a few dozen kilo-octets of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a giga-octets capacity, or even mega-octets.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology that serves instantaneous avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entry into serially manufactured cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its integration into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
