Industrial prices continued to increase
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - the Central Statistical Office of Hungary reported.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to one year ago, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of the fluctuations in domestic prices and exports, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only progressed to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry were only slightly higher by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with the production of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of primary plastic and chemical materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1.6 per cent).
This was the result of a deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), and a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have recorded an increase, between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent an important weight in national industrial operation, prices have risen by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, these are the prices of the oil processing sector that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the manufacture of metallurgical products, there was an increase in prices of 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverages and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have taken place in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent) and in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole of the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trading groups and according to sector allocation, in August, these are the investment profit-initiating sectors that have shown the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials producing sectors for subsequent processing did not change compared with the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase was observed in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, there was a fall of 1.4 per cent.
Sales prices for exports from the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
