The image offered by the filmmaker Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates what is happening in the large Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of mono-room consumption in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that we find unelectable and undisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical and memory-sponsored places, "It's like one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a lot of road and so many emotions" observes the actor of the Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, a film that offered to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and who told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia in a way of living the cinema, may be lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: these past five years, 316 traditional-type cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that paid mainly the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is headed by 82 single rooms, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
