"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a farm room in a city, these frequencies are not necessarily ready to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit for traders: the State's previous debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is a shame that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million per year.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian town, which is concerned about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mary and Anec, the first of which in Italy, to defend and promote mono cinemas in historical and peripheral centers.
The proposed regulations include tax relief measures for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I am pleased to note" by Giuseppe Tornatore, and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is clear, however, that in contrast to the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve sound and image quality, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria SuperCinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Paradise cinema" that I have been thinking of for 10 years.
